  <section class="hero-ecosystem">
    <h1>Ecosystem Service Valuation</h1>
    <p>
      Russia Dock Woodlands and Stave Hill Ecological Park are a high-use urban nature site
      with biodiversity, wellbeing, and education value. This page explains why ecosystem
      services are worth valuing and how different valuation methods help make these benefits
      more visible for planning, funding, and stakeholder alignment.
    </p>

    <div class="hero-badges">
      <span>Public goods</span>
      <span>Urban nature</span>
      <span>Planning and funding</span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main class="page-container">

    <section class="intro-panel">
      <h2>Why value ecosystem services here?</h2>
      <p>
        Russia Dock Woodlands and Stave Hill are a high-use urban nature site with biodiversity,
        wellbeing, and education value.
      </p>
      <p>
        Management decisions involve trade-offs: access vs. disturbance, “tidy” vs. wild,
        and short-term fixes vs. long-term resilience.
      </p>
      <p>
        Many benefits are public goods and remain invisible in budgets and planning.
        Valuation helps make these benefits decision-ready for planning, funding,
        and stakeholder alignment.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>What are ecosystem services?</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        Ecosystem services describe how nature supports human life and wellbeing.
        In the presentation, they are grouped into four broad categories.
      </p>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Provisioning</h3>
          <p>
            Food, water, raw materials, and other resources that ecosystems can provide.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Regulating</h3>
          <p>
            Climate regulation, water regulation, air quality, and other processes that
            help stabilise environmental conditions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Cultural</h3>
          <p>
            Recreation, identity, learning, and the wider social and educational value
            people gain from nature.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Supporting</h3>
          <p>
            Soil, habitat, and nutrient cycles that underpin the wider health and
            functioning of the ecosystem.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Protecting ecosystems</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        The presentation explains that ecosystems are natural capital: they provide a stock
        of resources and ecological processes. Ecosystem services are the flows of benefits
        people obtain from these ecosystems.
      </p>

      <p>
        These services do not operate in isolation. Their delivery depends on the interaction
        between natural capital, built capital, human capital, and social capital.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p>
          <strong>Example:</strong> Fish as food is not provided by ecosystems alone.
          It also depends on built capital such as boats and transport, human capital such as
          fishing knowledge and skills, and social capital such as rules, institutions,
          and access rights.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Why valuation matters</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        Many ecosystem services are public goods. They are often under-priced or not priced
        at all in markets. Provisioning and cultural services are easier to recognise because
        people experience them directly, while regulating services such as climate regulation
        are often indirect, long-term, and less visible.
      </p>

      <p>
        A key issue is imperfect information. People may undervalue ecosystem services if they
        do not understand their benefits, and these contributions are often overlooked in policy
        and land-use decisions.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p>
          <strong>Valuation makes trade-offs visible.</strong> It helps show why nature is
          often under-recognised in policy and investment decisions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>From valuation to application</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        The literature review also highlights wider lessons for classification and practice.
        Early frameworks provided a useful starting point, but clearer classification is needed.
      </p>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Classification matters</h3>
          <p>
            Early frameworks were useful, but ecosystem services need clearer and more
            practical classification.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Services and dis-services</h3>
          <p>
            Ecosystems can create both services and dis-services, so valuation must take
            account of complexity rather than only positive effects.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Urban context</h3>
          <p>
            Urban areas can generate high ecosystem service value because benefits reach many
            people through dense social, built, and economic interactions.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Decision relevance</h3>
          <p>
            The aim is not just theory, but making ecosystem benefits more useful for real
            planning and management decisions.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Valuation methods used in the project</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        The presentation compared several different ways of valuing ecosystem services at
        Russia Dock Woodlands and Stave Hill Ecological Park.
      </p>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Method 1: Hedonic pricing</h3>
          <p>
            Uses housing market data to estimate how much people are willing to pay for
            environmental quality. In this project, housing transaction data were combined
            with spatial park data, and distance from each property to the park was calculated
            using QGIS before regression analysis was conducted in Stata.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Method 2: Holistic valuation</h3>
          <p>
            Treats the park as natural capital and uses land value as a proxy for the wider
            value of ecosystem services. The method estimates the park’s natural capital value
            from park area and residential land value, then derives annual ecosystem service
            value using a 5% return.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Method 3 and 4: ESVD and benefit transfer</h3>
          <p>
            Uses the Ecosystem Service Value Database (ESVD), which standardises values in
            international dollars per hectare per year. The project applies these values to
            GIS-based habitat areas and compares an urban-based transfer route with a
            biome-based transfer route.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Method 5: Willingness to pay</h3>
          <p>
            Uses survey responses to estimate how much local people are willing to contribute
            annually to support the park. Respondents were also asked which improvements should
            be prioritised, such as clearer signage, dog-related management, infrastructure,
            wetland restoration, accessibility, and nature education.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Key findings from the results</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="two-column">
        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>Hedonic pricing results</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Properties within 500 metres of the park were estimated to sell at about 7.7% higher prices.</li>
            <li>Average house price within 500 metres: £586,419.</li>
            <li>Number of properties: 732.</li>
            <li>Estimated capitalised ecosystem service value: £33 million.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>Holistic valuation results</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Total park area used in the calculation: 13.18 hectares.</li>
            <li>Estimated natural capital value: £509,670,600.</li>
            <li>Estimated annual ecosystem service value: £25.5 million per year.</li>
            <li>Benefits include recreation and wellbeing, biodiversity habitat, climate regulation, and neighbourhood attractiveness.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="two-column">
        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>Benefit transfer results</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Urban studies approach: approximately £299.6 million per year.</li>
            <li>Biome studies approach: approximately £936,800 per year.</li>
            <li>The difference reflects whether values are driven more by urban demand and property effects, or by ecological functions alone.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>Willingness to pay results</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Total respondents: 74.</li>
            <li>Positive WTP responses: 51 (69%).</li>
            <li>Mean WTP: about £45 per person per year.</li>
            <li>Estimated local annual contribution: approximately £483,566 to £562,747.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>What local people prioritised</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        The survey results suggest that people are willing to pay for visible, practical
        improvements. The most important improvement identified in the presentation was
        clearer signage and information.
      </p>

      <div class="card-grid">
        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Top priorities</h3>
          <p>
            Clearer signage and information, safety and anti-social behaviour, and more
            infrastructure such as seating and lighting.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Ecological priorities</h3>
          <p>
            Wetland and waterbody restoration, wildlife-friendly habitat management,
            and nature educational activities.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Management priorities</h3>
          <p>
            Dog-related management, litter management, facility maintenance,
            and improved accessibility.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="info-card">
          <h3>Community priorities</h3>
          <p>
            More opportunities for community engagement and practical improvements that
            strengthen everyday use of the park.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Implications for policy and community wellbeing</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="two-column">
        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>For planning and policy</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Making hidden trade-offs visible.</li>
            <li>Revealing the true cost of development when ecosystems are otherwise treated as having zero value.</li>
            <li>Supporting environmental taxes, PES schemes, and conservation funding.</li>
            <li>Encouraging new institutions for public goods and shared environmental governance.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="house-box">
          <h3>For community wellbeing</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Showing the interdependence between economy, ecology, and social systems.</li>
            <li>Highlighting that ecosystem degradation can disproportionately affect vulnerable groups.</li>
            <li>Supporting nature-based solutions such as wetlands for flood protection.</li>
            <li>Strengthening community claims to protect shared ecosystems.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-block">
      <div class="section-title">
        <div class="bar"></div>
        <h2>Key takeaway</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <p>
          <strong>The main message is simple:</strong> Russia Dock Woodlands and Stave Hill
          Ecological Park generate significant ecological, social, and economic value.
          Ecosystem service valuation helps make these benefits more visible and more useful
          for real decisions about planning, management, conservation, and community wellbeing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

